48.title: Insect bites
dlg:
The reactions are usually immediate burning, transient pain, and itching, with an area of redness, swelling and induration up to a few inches across.

Swelling and redness usually peak at 48 hours, can last for a week and involve an entire part of the body like the arm, hand, neck or leg.

They are toxic caterpillars that resemble a tuft of cotton or fur with color varying from yellow to gray to reddish brown.

Puss moth caterpillars live in shade trees and shrubbery around homes and schools and in parks.

When a puss moth caterpillar presses against the skin, hairs become embedded in the skin and these can cause significant reactions.

These reactions include severe throbbing pain, burning, and a rash with red spots.

Treatments for the skin reactions may include putting tape on the site and pulling it off to remove the embedded hairs.

20.header:
Know this:
Some insect bites or stings will produce swelling.

If you were just bitten or felt like you were stung by something, remove any rings you may have on the finger, lips and so on. These places may swell.

21.header: Do you know the type of insect that bit you?

22.header:

Most reactions insect bites cause may be similar. Let's see what a pharmacist recommend to help with an insect bite that is available over the counter.

Would you like to do this, visit the nearest urgent care clinic or continue if you have no idea what insect bit you?

30.header:
No clue?
That's alright. Let's try to figure it out.

The most common questions regarding insect bites are:

  • Does this look like a mosquito bite?
  • Is this a spider bite to you?
  • I have no idea what bite me. Can you tell?

It is always a good idea to take the time to know what bit you and take a picture of it if possible. This will help in case of a medical emergency that may require an antidote.

Let's see what we can come up with regarding what bit you.

31.header:
When bitten, did you feel an immediate pain and now the area is showing redness?

Wheal and flare?

32.header:
Yes?
We are thinking fire ant bites.

Symptoms and signs of a fire ant sting are immediate pain followed by a raised itchy area (wheal) and spreading (flare) lesion.

33.header:
Did you feel and immediate burning or transient pain?

With the affected area itching?

34.header:
Yes?
Suspecting being stung by honeybees, wasps, yellow jackets or hornets.

35.header:
Is the bite area red, swollen?

With induration (hardening) up to a few inch across?

36.header:
Yes?
Suspecting being stung by honeybees, bumblebees, wasps, yellow jackets or hornets.

The reactions are immediate burning, transient pain, and itching, with an area of redness, swelling and hardening up to a few inches across.

37.header:
Alright.
Those were signs of being stung by a bee or wasp family.

If this is not the case with you, then let's continue and see what else we can come up with

Or perhaps you would like to see what a pharmacist recommend over the counter.

40.header:
When bitten, did you feel an intense throbbing and burning pain?

And now you have a red spotty rash?

If you are very susceptible, you may experience:

  • Swelling
  • Headache
  • Abdominal pain
  • Nausea.

41.header:
Yes?
Probably rubbed or pressed against a Puss Moth caterpillar.

Tap on the "FYI" button for a brief description of the Puss Moth.

42.header:
Sometimes where the bite occurred and the pattern of the reaction can help determine what bit you.

Let's use this to narrow the cause down.

44.header:
Are the bite spots in groups of three or four?

And mainly on the ankles, around the waist, knees and elbow bends?

45.header:
We are thinking flea bites.

Pressing on the rash may make it turn white.

Would you like to get a pharmacist suggestion on how to take care of this or continue to see what esle may have bitten you?

46.header: Are they on the neck, face and ear area?

47.header:
Suspecting being bitten by black flies

Would you like to get a pharmacist suggestion on how to take care of this or continue to see what esle may have bitten you?

48.header: Let's see if you are looking at a spider bite.

50.header:
Most spider bites produce a harmless itching or stinging that goes away in a day or two.

But brown spiders (violin, fiddleback, brown recluse) and widow spiders (black widow) can be very dangerous.

Let's see what we can come up with.

51.header: When the bite occurred, did you feel a sharp, stinging pain like a pinprick?

53.header: Are there 2 puncture marks in the skin at the bite area?

54.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • You are more than likely looking at a black widow bite.

Do you want to see a nearby urgent care clinic to you from the discussions so far or continue for now?

55.header:
Those two questions were to eliminate a black widow bite.

According to the CDC, a bite from a black widow can be distinguished from other insect bites by the two puncture marks it makes in the skin.

The bite starts with a slight swelling and redness at the site. There is usually pain at the bite area which then spread to the chest, abdomen or the whole body.

If you suspect, this is the case, then seek urgent care. Else, let's continue.

57.header: Was this bite painless initially, then started getting itchy?

59.header:
Is there a bull's eye on the bite site?

This bull's eye may be red and slightly swollen.

60.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Looking at a possible brown spider bite.
  • This bull's eye will become larger, fill with blood, rupture and turn into an ulcer.

Take this seriously. Systemic effects such as fever, chills, nausea, vomiting, muscle pain, rash, seizures, hypotension, blood clots, blood cell destruction and kidney failure are possible and responsible for all reported deaths from brown spider.

61.header:
Those were the signs of a brown spider bite.

If you don't think it is a dangerous spider bite, let's see if it is a tick bite or something of that group or even a bed bug bite.

70.header:
Are the bite marks itchy and red?

Maybe with a darker red spot in the middle.

72.header: Are the marks located on the face, neck, arms, back, hands and torso?

74.header:
Are these marks arranged in a rough line?

Arranged in clusters?

75.header: Possibly bed bugs that bit you.

76.header:
Are you experiencing severe itching?

With red bumps that look like pimples on the affected areas?

In severe cases, the bite may look similar to the skin reaction from exposure to poison ivy

77.header:
Yes?
You may be looking at chigger bites.

Bites that lead to severe itching usually occur about 3 to 6 hours after the chiggers attach to the skin.

Most chigger bites occur in thin-skinned areas of the body like the ankles, waist, groin, armpits and backs of knees.

A skin rash may appear on parts of the body that are exposed and this rash may stop where clothes meet the legs. This is often a clue that the rash is due to chigger bites.

78.header: Was there a tick logged on your skin and now you are seeing a rash?

80.header: Are you experiencing fever or flu-like symptoms with this bite?

81.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Looking at a tick bite
  • Seek urgent care clinic. Nothing over-the-counter will take care of this.

82.header:
Are you experiencing itchy, soft, pale bumps?

That are pink or red?

If you are highly sensitive, you may have a much larger area of itching.

Bear in mind, that these signs may not have appeared for up to 2 days after the bite.

83.header:
Yes?
More than likely looking at mosquito bites.

If a mosquito bite seems to be associated with more serious signs and symptoms - such as fever, severe headaches, body aches, nausea and vomiting - contact the doctor or visit the nearest urgent care clinic.

Eczema (Atopic dermatitis) causes itchy and dry skin. Let's figure this out.

We will talk about adult eczema here. If this is for a child, see the children section for more specific discussion (coming soon).

1.header: Let's see if you are looking at eczema in the first place.

2.header:
You are experiencing dry skin all over the body.

Is this why you think you have eczema?

3.header:
Yes?
OK. Eczema can cause this. So can other things, let's continue.

4.header: Are you having itching that later turns to a skin rash?

5.header:
Yes?
This is a symptom of eczema.
 (The itch that rashes)

It sometimes start with itching and later turn into a skin rash.

6.header: Do you have skin blisters with oozing and crusting?

7.header:
Yes?
Eczema can cause blisters with oozing and crusting.

8.header: Do you have rash inside the knees and/or elbows?

9.header:
Yes?

10.header: What about rash on the hands and feet?

11.header:

12.header:
Rash on the neck.
Is that why you are thinking eczema?

13.header:
Yes?

14.header: Do you have bumpy skin on the back of the arms?

16.header: What about bumpy skin on front of the thigh?

17.header:
Alright.
This is a sign of eczema.

18.header:
Great.

If you think you may be looking at eczema, let's continue to find out if you need to see a doctor or if you can take care of this with over-the-counter measures.
